Five feedstocks were prepared for pyrolysis under different conditions. These were each of the four individual dried food wastes and an equal-weighted mixture of the four wastes. Pyrolysis was conducted in the absence of oxygen using a muffle furnace (Lindberg Blue M-3504, Thermo Scientific) in batch mode at the following temperatures to assess their influence on biochar yield and properties: 300, 400, 500 and 600 °C (Xue et al. 2019). Fifty grams of each dried feedstock was pyrolyzed at the four different temperature conditions to produce biochar. Samples were put in a furnace and raised to the defined temperature at a ramp rate of 5 °C min−1 and held at the desired temperature for 15 min. After pyrolysis, the samples were left inside the furnace to cool down and then weighed to determine the yield by the equation below:1Yield of biochar%=Weight of biochargWeight of oven-dried wastesg×100.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
